{"title_page": "Union de Industrias Militares", "text_new": "{{short description|State-owned Cuban weapons manufacturer}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name=Uni\u00f3n de Industrias Militares\n|logo     = \n|type             = \n|foundation       = 22 December 1988<ref name=\"globsec\" />\n|location_city    = \n|location_country =[[Cuba]]\n|key_people       =[[Luis P\u00e9rez R\u00f3spide]] (former head)<ref name=\"Klepak\" />\n|industry         =[[Arms industry|Defence]]\n|net_income       = \n|num_employees    = \n|caption          = \n|homepage         =\n|footnotes        = \n|intl             = \n}}\n\nThe '''Uni\u00f3n de Industrias Militares''' ('''UIM''', [[English language|English]]: Union of Military Industries) is the state owned military-industrial complex in [[Cuba]]. It is responsible for the repair of the weaponry and technology of the ground, air and naval units of the [[Cuban Revolutionary Armed Forces]] as well as the production of light weapons for infantry, ammunition, mines and other equipment. The UIM also devotes part of its production and service capacity to serving other requirements of the Cuban economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141108030810/http://www.cubagob.cu/otras_info/minfar/defensa_ingles/iindustria/iindustria.htm|title=Cuban military industry|date=2014-11-08|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe group has its origins in the 1960s with the creation of the ''Empresas Militares Industriales'' (EMI, [[English language|English]]: Industrial Military Companies) after the [[Cuban Revolution]]. The group initially operated repair bases for the military. Throughout the [[Cold War]], the military industry  produced equipment under licence and oversaw the maintenance of equipment, much of it transferred from the [[Soviet Union]].<ref name=\"globsec\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/cuba/industry.htm|title=Union of War Industry|last=|first=|date=2019-02-21|website=Global Security|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nAfter the end of the [[Cold War]], during the [[Special Period]] of economic hardship of the 1990s, the UIM was given the new responsibility to \"contribute to the economic development of the country and the self-financing of the armed forces\". Thus, orders were given to convert part of the industry to civilian needs, with emphasis on nick, fruit, and other foodstuffs. By 1996, some 30% of the UIM's responsibilities were for the civilian sector.<ref name=\"Klepak\" />\n\n== Facilities ==\nThe UIM is composed of twelve industrial military companies, seven research and development centers, and two centers of scientific-technological services throughout the country.<ref name=\"globsec\" /> Operating out of sixteen industrial installations, approximately 230 factories and companies are involved in total.<ref name=\"Klepak\">{{Cite book|last=Klepak|first=H.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=1fHFAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA339&lpg=PA339&dq=%22union+of+military+industry%22+cuba&source=bl&ots=KEFtcLURZY&sig=odJ01PpwZWV-c8V6RnLARLu6XYw&hl=en&sa=X&ei=sU1uVbjWBM2I7AbeyoLADw&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=UIM&f=false|title=Cuba\u2019s Military 1990\u20132005: Revolutionary Soldiers During Counter-Revolutionary Times|date=2005-10-20|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-4039-8060-1|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsgroups.derkeiler.com/Archive/Soc/soc.culture.cuba/2006-08/msg00376.html|title=MANY SECTORS CONTROLLED BY MILITARY|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\n* [[Mambi AMR]]\n* [[Alejandro Sniper Rifle]]\n* Fiero fast attack vehicle\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cubagob.cu/otras_info/minfar/defensa_ingles/iindustria/iindustria.htm Cuban military industry page on Cuba government's website]\n\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Defence companies of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Firearm manufacturers of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Military\u2013industrial complex]]\n[[Category:Military vehicle manufacturers]]\n\n{{cuba-stub}}\n{{mil-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|State-owned Cuban weapons manufacturer}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name=Uni\u00f3n de Industrias Militares\n|logo     = \n|type             = \n|foundation       = 22 December 1988<ref name=\"globsec\" />\n|location_city    = \n|location_country =[[Cuba]]\n|key_people       =[[Luis P\u00e9rez R\u00f3spide]] (former head)<ref name=\"Klepak\" />\n|industry         =[[Arms industry|Defence]]\n|net_income       = \n|num_employees    = \n|caption          = \n|homepage         =\n|footnotes        = \n|intl             = \n}}\n\nThe '''Uni\u00f3n de Industrias Militares''' ('''UIM''', [[English language|English]]: Union of Military Industries) is the state owned military-industrial complex in [[Cuba]]. It is responsible for the repair of the weaponry and technology of the ground, air and naval units of the [[Cuban Revolutionary Armed Forces]] as well as the production of light weapons for infantry, ammunition, mines and other equipment. The UIM also devotes part of its production and service capacity to serving other requirements of the Cuban economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141108030810/http://www.cubagob.cu/otras_info/minfar/defensa_ingles/iindustria/iindustria.htm|title=Cuban military industry|date=2014-11-08|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe group has its origins in the 1960s with the creation of the Empresas Militares Industriales (EMI, [[English language|English]]: Industrial Military Companies) after the [[Cuban Revolution]]. The group initially operated repair bases for the military. Throughout the [[Cold War]], the military industry  produced equipment under licence and oversaw the maintenance of equipment, much of it transferred from the [[Soviet Union]].<ref name=\"globsec\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/cuba/industry.htm|title=Union of War Industry|last=|first=|date=2019-02-21|website=Global Security|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nAfter the end of the [[Cold War]], during the [[Special Period]] of economic hardship of the 1990s, the UIM was given the new responsibility to \"contribute to the economic development of the country and the self-financing of the armed forces\". Thus, orders were given to convert part of the industry to civilian needs, with emphasis on nick, fruit, and other foodstuffs. By 1996, some 30% of the UIM's responsibilities were for the civilian sector.<ref name=\"Klepak\" />\n\n== Facilities ==\nThe UIM is composed of twelve industrial military companies, seven research and development centers, and two centers of scientific-technological services throughout the country.<ref name=\"globsec\" /> Operating out of sixteen industrial installations, approximately 230 factories and companies are involved in total.<ref name=\"Klepak\">{{Cite book|last=Klepak|first=H.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=1fHFAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA339&lpg=PA339&dq=%22union+of+military+industry%22+cuba&source=bl&ots=KEFtcLURZY&sig=odJ01PpwZWV-c8V6RnLARLu6XYw&hl=en&sa=X&ei=sU1uVbjWBM2I7AbeyoLADw&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=UIM&f=false|title=Cuba\u2019s Military 1990\u20132005: Revolutionary Soldiers During Counter-Revolutionary Times|date=2005-10-20|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-4039-8060-1|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsgroups.derkeiler.com/Archive/Soc/soc.culture.cuba/2006-08/msg00376.html|title=MANY SECTORS CONTROLLED BY MILITARY|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\n* [[Mambi AMR]]\n* [[Alejandro Sniper Rifle]]\n* Fiero fast attack vehicle\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cubagob.cu/otras_info/minfar/defensa_ingles/iindustria/iindustria.htm Cuban military industry page on Cuba government's website]\n\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Defence companies of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Firearm manufacturers of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Military\u2013industrial complex]]\n[[Category:Military vehicle manufacturers]]\n\n{{cuba-stub}}\n{{mil-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lollipoplollipoplollipop", "label": "safe", "comment": "Italics round Spanish", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Union_de_Industrias_Militares"}
